english:
  title: To Jung, the Grand Commandant
  author: Gwon Han-gong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A fair one dwells beyond the veil of clouds,
    Yet mountains tower high and waters run deep—
    The path is treacherous, the crossing hard.
    I long to follow, but the seasons turn,
    And in the distant sky the birds fly swift and free.
    Who knows what becomes of me, scratching my head in silence
    As daylight fades, while autumn wind
    Comes whistling through, sweeping the yellow leaves away?
  footnotes:
    - Jung, the Grand Commandant (鄭司空) was likely a contemporary or acquaintance of the poet, and the 'fair one' may refer to a lady of virtue or the addressee himself, using classical poetic convention of the beautiful person as a figure of virtue or longing.
    - The poem employs the classical Chinese trope of separation by natural barriers as a metaphor for emotional or social distance that cannot be bridged.
